intent: >
  Bring the alert path online end-to-end. DowntimeAlertMailer fires
  via .deliver_later when PerformCheckJob detects a fresh flip to down.
  letter_opener_web makes the result visible in dev without configuring
  SMTP. This is the slice that turns "we record check results" into
  "we tell you when your site goes down."

slice: 5/8
kind: feature
behavior_change: additive

reversibility: reversible
# New code only, no schema, no migration. Gemfile + dev config changes
# revert cleanly. No external state touched.

scope:
  declared:
    - app/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer.rb
    - app/views/downtime_alert_mailer/site_down.html.erb
    - app/views/downtime_alert_mailer/site_down.text.erb
    - spec/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer_spec.rb
    - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
    - Gemfile
    - Gemfile.lock
    - config/environments/development.rb
    - config/routes.rb
  actual:
    - app/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer.rb
    - app/views/downtime_alert_mailer/site_down.html.erb
    - app/views/downtime_alert_mailer/site_down.text.erb
    - spec/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer_spec.rb
    - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
    - Gemfile
    - Gemfile.lock
    - config/environments/development.rb
    - config/routes.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop app/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer.rb spec/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer_spec.rb app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb config/environments/development.rb config/routes.rb Gemfile
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "Recipient comes from ENV['DORM_GUARD_ALERT_TO'] with a fallback to alerts@dorm-guard.local. The .local TLD is a deliberate trip-wire — anything actually trying to deliver to it will fail loudly, which is what we want when production forgets to set the env var."
  - "Alert email mentions only the site (name + URL), not the failing CheckResult. The failure detail belongs on the dashboard (slice 7), not in an email body that has to render in 10 different mail clients. Keeping the email sparse also dodges the need to expose has_many :check_results from this slice."
  - "Flip detection rule: previous_status was anything-but-down AND current status is down. This means unknown→down fires the first-ever alert and up→down fires on regression, while down→down stays silent (no spam) and down→up stays silent (no recovery emails this slice). Recovery emails are a future concern."
  - ".deliver_later, not .deliver_now. Mail goes through ActiveJob → Solid Queue, so a slow SMTP server can't block PerformCheckJob's transaction-bracketing or the rest of its work. Cost: an extra job per flip-to-down, which is a price worth paying for keeping the check loop snappy."
  - "letter_opener_web is mounted under `if Rails.env.development?`, so the route doesn't leak into the production routing table or cause boot warnings in test."
  - "DowntimeAlertMailer is enqueued in the job spec via rspec-rails' have_enqueued_mail matcher. We do NOT mock the mailer — the matcher inspects ActiveJob's test queue, which means we're asserting the real side effect (a job got enqueued with the right params), not stubbing the contract we're trying to verify."

deviations_from_plan: >
  Plan originally said slice 4 should "enqueue DowntimeAlertJob on a
  up→down flip" and slice 5 should be the mailer. The flip enqueue
  was deferred from slice 4 to here (documented in slice 4's note).
  No DowntimeAlertJob was created — Rails' .deliver_later already
  hands off to ActiveJob, so a separate job class would be a wrapper
  around the mailer that adds nothing.

trade_offs: >
  notify_if_newly_down runs OUTSIDE the persistence transaction.
  Considered the alternative — wrapping the mailer enqueue inside the
  same transaction so an enqueue failure would roll back the
  CheckResult — and rejected it: losing an alert is recoverable
  (operator can see "down" on the dashboard within a minute), losing
  the check history is not. Atomicity over the wrong boundary is
  worse than no atomicity. Surfaced the ordering choice in the
  reviewer_attention pointers.

self_review:
  consistency: >
    First mailer in the repo. Sets the pattern: ENV-fetched recipient
    with a sentinel default, sparse parallel html+text views, mailer
    parameters via .with(...) (the modern Rails idiom), .deliver_later
    at every call site. Future mailers should follow this shape or
    consciously diverge.
  metz: >
    `perform` stayed at 5 body lines by extracting `notify_if_newly_down`.
    `notify_if_newly_down` is 4 lines, clean. `record_check` is still
    7 physical lines from slice 4 (5-keyword create!) — same edge case
    as before, not regressed by this slice.
  mocking: >
    HttpChecker remains mocked at the seam in the job spec (we own it).
    DowntimeAlertMailer is NOT mocked — `have_enqueued_mail` matches
    against the real ActiveJob test queue, so we're asserting the
    actual side effect, not stubbing the thing we want to verify.
  error_paths: >
    Mailer enqueue runs OUTSIDE the persistence transaction, on
    purpose. If `deliver_later` raises (serialization, queue down,
    etc.), the CheckResult and Site.status update still commit. We'd
    rather lose an alert (operator can see "down" on the dashboard
    within a minute) than lose check history. Trade-off explicit, not
    incidental.
  security: >
    @site.name is interpolated into the email subject. Mail::Field
    sanitizes header values, so even an adversarial site name like
    "Example\r\nBcc: attacker@evil.com" cannot inject headers. Checked
    + mitigated by the framework, but worth flagging because the
    mitigation is implicit. If we ever build the subject manually or
    bypass mail()'s header construction, this protection goes away.
  api: >
    DowntimeAlertMailer.site_down is a new public mailer action, called
    from one place (PerformCheckJob#notify_if_newly_down). If a future
    "site recovered" mailer lands, it should follow the same shape:
    one action per event, .with(site:) params, deliver_later from the
    job that detects the transition.

confidence: high

reviewer_attention:
  - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb:8-9      # notify call OUTSIDE the transaction — atomicity boundary decision
  - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb:45-50    # the flip-detection rule itself (the truth table)
  - app/mailers/downtime_alert_mailer.rb:6 # ENV.fetch recipient with sentinel default
